<section id="accusation">
  <h2>What the Accusation Is</h2>

  <p>The question "Is OLSP Academy a scam or an MLM?" appears with striking frequency across online communities. Independent research identifies this as the single most common question about OLSP, appearing across Reddit, Trustpilot, Quora, and independent review platforms <span class="rel-label verified">Verified</span>.</p>

  <p>The accusation carries significant emotional weight. Community discussions reveal four distinct fears: wasting money on a program that does not deliver, wasting months of effort with nothing to show, looking foolish by promoting a program friends and family will recognise as MLM-adjacent, and missing out on a genuine opportunity. Trust and money are at stake simultaneously <span class="rel-label verified">Verified</span>.</p>

  <div class="callout warn">
    <strong>Important:</strong> Community members have raised these accusations, but no legal or regulatory body has made a finding that OLSP Academy operates as an illegal pyramid scheme. The accusation exists in public discussion, not in any court or regulator ruling.
  </div>

  <p>The difficulty for prospective members is that the available information is structurally biased. Positive reviews almost all come from OLSP affiliates who earn commissions. Negative reviews may come from people who gave up or never joined. Independent review sites that cover OLSP are split roughly evenly, with the negative side specifically noting that most positive reviews come from members who are themselves promoting OLSP <span class="rel-label third-party">Third-Party Reported</span>. As one independent reviewer puts it, there is no "neutral, evidence-based assessment that separates the legal definition from the practical experience" <span class="rel-label third-party">Third-Party Reported</span>.</p>

  <p>This article exists to fill that gap. We will not tell you whether OLSP is an MLM. We will give you the legal framework, the factual evidence, and a set of questions to answer for yourself — and then you decide.</p>
</section>

<section id="legal-definition">
  <h2>The Legal Definition of MLM</h2>

  <p>Before we can evaluate OLSP, we need a clear, authoritative definition of what an MLM is — and more importantly, what distinguishes a legal MLM from an illegal pyramid scheme.</p>

  <h3>The FTC Framework</h3>

  <p>The US Federal Trade Commission (FTC) defines an illegal pyramid scheme as an enterprise "characterised by the payment by participants of money to the company in return for which they receive (1) the right to sell a product and (2) the right to receive in return for recruiting other participants into the program rewards which are unrelated to the sale of the product to ultimate users" <span class="rel-label verified">Verified</span>. This definition comes from the 1975 <em>Koscot</em> court decision and remains the canonical legal standard.</p>

  <p>The FTC explicitly states there is no percentage-based safe harbour. There is no rule that says "if commissions from recruitment stay below X%, it is legal." Instead, the FTC evaluates the entire business model on a case-by-case basis, examining multiple factors <span class="rel-label verified">Verified</span>.</p>

  <h3>Key FTC Evaluation Criteria</h3>

  <p>The FTC looks at the following factors to distinguish a legal MLM from an illegal pyramid scheme <span class="rel-label verified">Verified</span>:</p>

  <div class="table-scroll">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Factor</th>
          <th>What the FTC Examines</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Incentive structure</td>
          <td>What behaviour does the compensation plan incentivise — recruitment or product sales?</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Income expectations</td>
          <td>What earnings claims does the marketing create, and are they substantiated?</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Training and messaging</td>
          <td>What are participants taught to prioritise — selling products or recruiting?</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Entry motivation</td>
          <td>Why do people actually sign up — to earn from sales or to earn from recruitment?</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Actual earnings</td>
          <td>How do participants actually make money in practice, not just in theory?</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Customer base</td>
          <td>Who buys the products — actual external customers or participants themselves?</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Participant losses</td>
          <td>Do participants experience financial losses, which the FTC notes are "inevitable due to the structure of the pyramid scheme"?</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="callout info">
    <strong>Key takeaway:</strong> There is no single yes/no test. The FTC evaluates the whole picture. A program can have some MLM-like features without being an illegal pyramid scheme — and it can be a legal MLM while still being a bad fit for many people.
  </div>
</section>

<section id="how-it-works">
  <h2>How OLSP Academy Operates</h2>

  <p>To evaluate OLSP against the FTC framework, we need to understand its pricing structure, commission system, and what members actually promote. The following data comes from multiple independent reviewers who are current members, cross-referenced with OLSP's own vendor sales pages.</p>

  <h3>Pricing Structure</h3>

  <p>OLSP Academy's pricing spans from free to $6,500. The tiered structure is documented consistently by multiple independent reviewers <span class="rel-label third-party">Third-Party Reported</span>:</p>

  <div class="table-scroll">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Tier</th>
          <th>Cost</th>
          <th>What It Includes</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Free</td>
          <td>$0</td>
          <td>Basic training content, limited access</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Mega Link</td>
          <td>$7 one-time</td>
          <td>Entry-level affiliate link system, basic training</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Magick Link</td>
          <td>$47 one-time</td>
          <td>Enhanced link system with additional features</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Live Profit Builders</td>
          <td>$49/month or $497/year</td>
          <td>Live training, community access, weekly coaching calls</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Team Builders / Community Builders</td>
          <td>$199/month or $997–$1,997 one-time</td>
          <td>Full system access, 2-tier commissions, done-for-you funnels, CRM, autoresponder, page builder</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>VIP</td>
          <td>$6,500 (by application only)</td>
          <td>Personal coaching, high-level strategy, advanced tools</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="callout warn">
    <strong>Important caveat:</strong> OLSP's official terms of service and commission documentation are accessible only to logged-in members and could not be independently verified at the time of writing. Pricing and tier data in this section comes from multiple independent reviewers (theolspacademy.com affiliate page claims a "$497 launch offer" which may refer to a specific promotion rather than a standard tier).
  </div>

  <h3>Commission Structure</h3>

  <p>OLSP Academy's commission system operates on multiple levels <span class="rel-label third-party">Third-Party Reported</span>:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>100% commissions</strong> on Mega Link front-end sales — affiliates keep the full $7</li>
    <li><strong>40%–60% commission rates</strong> on most products across the catalogue</li>
    <li><strong>2-tier (second-level) commissions</strong> at the Team Builders/Community Builders tier — affiliates earn from their direct referrals' sales and from their referrals' referrals</li>
    <li><strong>Up to $2,500 per high-ticket sale</strong> for the Team Builders program, according to OLSP's vendor sales page <span class="rel-label vendor">Vendor Claim</span> (the rate is confirmed by multiple independent reviewers, though actual earnings depend on execution)</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="callout key">
    <strong>Critical finding:</strong> The 2-tier commission structure at the Team Builders level is what draws MLM comparisons. This is the structural characteristic that most clearly overlaps with MLM compensation models. Multiple independent reviewers agree on this point.
  </div>

  <h3>What Members Promote</h3>

  <p>The product catalogue members promote consists primarily of OLSP's own membership tiers and marketing tools. Independent reviewers note that OLSP training focuses on teaching members to promote OLSP products <span class="rel-label third-party">Third-Party Reported</span>. One long-term member (4+ years at Community Builders level) describes the system as "worth it only if committed to selling OLSP products" <span class="rel-label third-party">Third-Party Reported</span>.</p>

  <p>This is a significant structural characteristic: the primary source of commissions is recruitment into OLSP's own membership tiers, not sales of third-party products. In MLM terminology, the product is the membership itself.</p>

  <p>OLSP's marketing materials claim "50,000+ Active Students," "$50M+ Student Earnings," and "4.8/5 Trustpilot Rating" on their affiliate sales page <span class="rel-label vendor">Vendor Claim</span>. None of these figures could be independently verified. In fact, the actual Trustpilot TrustScore is 4.2/5 from 209 reviews, not 4.8/5 <span class="rel-label self-reported">Self-Reported</span>.</p>
</section>

<section id="evaluation">
  <h2>MLM Characteristics: Where OLSP Fits</h2>

  <p>With the FTC framework in hand and OLSP's structure documented, we can now evaluate OLSP against each MLM characteristic. This is the most important section of the article — the evidence-based answer you came for.</p>

  <div class="table-scroll">
    <table class="evidence-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>MLM Characteristic</th>
          <th>OLSP Status</th>
          <th>Source Reliability</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Requires recruitment to earn</td>
          <td><strong>No.</strong> Members can earn commissions from direct sales of Mega Link and other products without recruiting anyone. The $7 entry tier pays 100% commission on direct sales.</td>
          <td><span class="rel-label third-party">Third-Party Reported</span></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>2-tier (or more) commission structure</td>
          <td><strong>Yes, at higher tiers.</strong> The Team Builders/Community Builders level includes 2-tier commissions. This is the structural characteristic that most closely matches MLM compensation models.</td>
          <td><span class="rel-label third-party">Third-Party Reported</span></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Primary product = membership / recruitment</td>
          <td><strong>Partially.</strong> Most commissions come from promoting OLSP's own membership tiers and marketing tools. Members are primarily selling access to the system itself.</td>
          <td><span class="rel-label third-party">Third-Party Reported</span></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>System growth depends on recruitment</td>
          <td><strong>Partially.</strong> Because the primary product is the membership itself, the system requires continuous new members to sustain commission flows. This is a structural feature of any program where members sell the program.</td>
          <td><span class="rel-label third-party">Third-Party Reported</span></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Large upfront entry fee</td>
          <td><strong>No.</strong> The minimum entry is $7, which is significantly lower than most MLM entry fees. However, the realistic investment for meaningful earning potential is $49–$199/month or more.</td>
          <td><span class="rel-label third-party">Third-Party Reported</span></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Inventory purchase requirements</td>
          <td><strong>No.</strong> There is no requirement to purchase inventory. Members promote digital products and memberships.</td>
          <td><span class="rel-label third-party">Third-Party Reported</span></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Earnings claims substantiated</td>
          <td><strong>No.</strong> OLSP does not publish member earnings data. Marketing claims of "$50M+ Student Earnings" and "$3,000–$10,000+ per month" are unverified <span class="rel-label vendor">Vendor Claim</span>. General MLM industry data indicates that 99% of MLM participants lose money — but this is an industry-wide figure, not OLSP-specific <span class="rel-label third-party">Third-Party Reported</span>.</td>
          <td><span class="rel-label unverified">Unverified</span></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Training emphasis</td>
          <td><strong>MLM-adjacent.</strong> Training teaches real marketing skills (email, traffic, list building) but focuses these skills primarily on promoting OLSP products. The skills are transferable but the application context is narrow.</td>
          <td><span class="rel-label third-party">Third-Party Reported</span></td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>The Core Finding</h3>

  <div class="summary-box">
    <h3>OLSP shares structural characteristics with MLMs but is not a legal pyramid scheme.</h3>
    <p>Independent reviewers consistently reach this conclusion <span class="rel-label third-party">Third-Party Reported</span>. The reasoning: OLSP does not require recruitment to earn (direct sales are always an option), it sells real digital products (training, tools, memberships), the entry barrier is $7 (not a large upfront fee), and commissions are available from direct product sales. However, the 2-tier commission structure, the focus on promoting the membership itself, and the system's dependence on continuous recruitment create significant structural overlap with MLM models.</p>
  </div>

  <p>One independent reviewer provides the most explicit analysis: "OLSP is not technically a multi-level marketing company in the legal sense. It does not require recruitment to participate, income can be generated from direct product sales, and the product catalogue contains real digital tools and training. It does, however, share structural characteristics with MLM" <span class="rel-label third-party">Third-Party Reported</span>.</p>

  <p>The distinction between "legal MLM" and "illegal pyramid scheme" is itself contested. Some community members categorically state OLSP is an MLM. The FTC itself recognises that legal MLMs can still cause participant harm — which is why it proposed a new Earnings Claims Rule for MLMs in January 2025 <span class="rel-label third-party">Third-Party Reported</span>.</p>

  <div class="callout warn">
    <strong>The unsatisfying truth:</strong> OLSP is not legally a pyramid scheme, but it operates in the same structural neighbourhood as MLMs. Whether that distinction matters depends on your personal tolerance for MLM-adjacent models — which is precisely what the next section addresses.
  </div>
</section>

<section id="nuance">
  <h2>Why the Answer Is Unsatisfying</h2>

  <p>If you reached this section hoping for a simple yes or no, you are not alone. The community discussions show that most people want a binary answer: "Is it an MLM, yes or no?" The evidence does not support a binary answer.</p>

  <p>There are three reasons the MLM question about OLSP cannot be answered with a simple yes or no:</p>

  <h3>1. The legal definition is situational, not mechanical</h3>
  <p>The FTC evaluates business models holistically, not by checking boxes. Two programs with identical commission structures could receive different evaluations based on how they train members, what earnings claims they make, and who actually buys their products. This means there is no definitive checklist for OLSP to pass or fail — only a judgment call based on all available evidence.</p>

  <h3>2. The available information is structurally biased</h3>
  <p>As documented earlier, every source of information about OLSP has a built-in bias. Positive sources have financial incentive. Negative sources may be uninformed or disgruntled. Even the Trustpilot data has limitations: the platform shows a 4.2/5 TrustScore from 209 reviews, though OLSP does not actively solicit reviews and the review volume is low relative to its claimed member base of 50,000+ <span class="rel-label self-reported">Self-Reported</span>.</p>

  <h3>3. "Legally acceptable" and "personally acceptable" are different questions</h3>
  <p>A program can be fully legal under FTC guidelines and still be a bad fit for you personally. The question you are really asking might not be "Is OLSP legally an MLM?" but rather "Will I be comfortable building my business in a system that shares MLM characteristics?" Those are different questions, and only you can answer the second one.</p>
</section>

<section id="decision-framework">
  <h2>Your Decision Framework</h2>

  <p>Instead of giving you a yes/no answer that the evidence cannot support, here are three questions to ask yourself. Your answers will tell you whether OLSP's structure is acceptable to you.</p>

  <div class="decision-box">
    <h3>Three Questions to Determine If OLSP Is Right for You</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong>Are you comfortable earning primarily from promoting the platform's own membership?</strong><br>
        If your goal is to promote a wide range of third-party products as an affiliate, OLSP may feel constraining. If you are comfortable with the primary product being the membership itself — as is the case with many training platforms — the structure may not bother you.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Does a 2-tier commission structure bother you?</strong><br>
        The Team Builders tier pays commissions two levels deep. This is the characteristic that most closely resembles MLM compensation. If the idea of earning from your referrals' referrals makes you uncomfortable, you may want to stay at lower tiers or choose a different platform. If you see it as a legitimate way to earn from team building, it may not be an issue.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Can you generate your own traffic without relying on built-in systems?</strong><br>
        OLSP provides training and tools, but independent reviewers consistently note that members still need to generate their own traffic. Community discussions document members who joined expecting automated traffic and earned nothing. If you have traffic generation skills or are willing to learn them independently, the system can work. If you expect built-in traffic to deliver results, you may be disappointed.
      </li>
    </ol>
  </div>

  <p>If you answered "no" to two or more of these questions, OLSP's structure may not be a comfortable fit — regardless of whether it meets the legal definition of an MLM. If you answered "yes" to all three, the structural questions are likely not a barrier for you.</p>

  <div class="callout info">
    <strong>What matters:</strong> The legal question is "Is OLSP an MLM?" The practical question is "Can this work for me?" Both are valid. This article answers the first with evidence. Only you can answer the second.
  </div>
</section>

<section id="conclusion">
  <h2>Conclusion: Your Call</h2>

  <p>OLSP Academy occupies a grey area. It is not an illegal pyramid scheme by the FTC's definition — no regulatory body has made such a finding, and the evidence does not support that conclusion. The $7 entry barrier is low, direct sales are always an option, and real digital products are sold.</p>

  <p>But OLSP also shares meaningful structural characteristics with MLMs. The 2-tier commission system, the focus on selling the membership itself, and the system's dependence on continuous recruitment create an environment that many people experience as MLM-adjacent. The community discussions make it clear: the MLM feel is real for many members, even if the legal definition is not satisfied.</p>

  <p>This article has presented the evidence, the legal framework, and the practical realities. We have not taken a side because the evidence does not support a single binary conclusion. What the evidence does support is your right to make an informed decision based on your own values, goals, and tolerance for MLM-adjacent structures.</p>

  <p>If you decide OLSP is worth exploring, the $7 Mega Link entry is low-risk enough to evaluate first-hand. If you decide it is not the right fit, that is a valid conclusion — and you now have the evidence to explain why, both to yourself and to anyone who asks.</p>

