<section id="faq">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>Is OLSP Academy a pyramid scheme?</summary>
    <p>No legal or regulatory body has found OLSP Academy to be a pyramid scheme. The FTC defines an illegal pyramid scheme by the relationship between recruitment rewards and product sales — and OLSP offers direct sales commissions from a $7 entry point without requiring recruitment. However, the 2-tier commission structure at the Team Builders level and the focus on selling the membership itself create structural similarities to MLM models that make community members uncomfortable.</p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Do I have to recruit people to make money at OLSP?</summary>
    <p>No. Members can earn commissions from direct sales of the Mega Link ($7) and other OLSP products without recruiting anyone. The 100% commission on Mega Link front-end sales is available to all members regardless of recruitment activity. Higher tiers (Team Builders/Community Builders) introduce 2-tier commissions, but even at those levels, direct sales are always an option <span class="rel-label third-party">Third-Party Reported</span>.</p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>How is OLSP different from Wealthy Affiliate or Legendary Marketer?</summary>
    <p>Like OLSP, both Wealthy Affiliate and Legendary Marketer are affiliate marketing training platforms with tiered memberships and affiliate programs for their own products. The structural differences are in the details: Wealthy Affiliate does not offer multi-tier commissions, while Legendary Marketer has a compensation plan that some critics also compare to MLM. Each platform should be evaluated individually against FTC criteria <span class="rel-label third-party">Third-Party Reported</span>.</p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Can I trust positive reviews of OLSP Academy?</summary>
    <p>Most positive reviews of OLSP come from members who earn affiliate commissions — including many of the independent review sites that rank for OLSP-related searches. This does not automatically make them wrong, but it means the reviewer has a financial interest in your decision. Cross-reference claims across multiple sources, look for reviewers who acknowledge their affiliate relationship, and prioritise sources that provide specific, verifiable data over general enthusiasm <span class="rel-label verified">Verified</span>.</p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>What percentage of OLSP members actually earn money?</summary>
    <p>OLSP Academy does not publish member earnings data. The only available earnings figures are self-reported in community discussions and cannot be independently verified <span class="rel-label unverified">Unverified</span>. Industry-wide, studies find that approximately 99% of MLM participants lose money across 350 US MLMs, but this is a general industry statistic, not specific to OLSP <span class="rel-label third-party">Third-Party Reported</span>.</p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Is the $7 entry point real, or is it a marketing gimmick?</summary>
    <p>The $7 Mega Link tier is real — multiple independent reviewers confirm it exists and pays 100% commission on front-end sales. However, the realistic investment for meaningful earning potential is significantly higher. Most reviewers estimate that Live Profit Builders ($49/month) or Team Builders ($199/month or $997 one-time) is where the training and tools become substantial enough to generate meaningful income <span class="rel-label third-party">Third-Party Reported</span>.</p>
  </details>
</section>

